c1\u03b9\u03b1\u03ba\u03ae \u03ad\u03bd\u03bd\u03bf\u03bc\u03b7 \u03c4\u03ac\u03be\u03b7 \u03c5\u03c0\u03cc \u03c4\u03bf \u03c0\u03c1\u03af\u03c3\u03bc\u03b1 \u03c4\u03b7\u03c2 \u0395\u03c5\u03c1\u03c9\u03c0\u03b1\u03ca\u03ba\u03ae\u03c2 \u03a3\u03cd\u03bc\u03b2\u03b1\u03c3\u03b7\u03c2 \u0394\u03b9\u03ba\u03b1\u03b9\u03c9\u03bc\u03ac\u03c4\u03c9\u03bd \u03c4\u03bf\u03c5 \u0391\u03bd\u03b8\u03c1\u03ce\u03c0\u03bf\u03c5 \u03ba\u03b1\u03b9 \u03c4\u03b7\u03c2 \u03b5\u03c5\u03c1\u03c9\u03c0\u03b1\u03ca\u03ba\u03ae\u03c2 \u039f\u03b4\u03b7\u03b3\u03af\u03b1\u03c2 2016\/343\/\u0395\u0395.<\/p>\n<p>Abstract <\/p>\n<p>The contribution of the European Court of Human Rights in the interpretation and application of the presumption of innocence as protected by Article 6.2 of the European Convention on Human Rights is indisputable. As a procedural guarantee in the context of criminal proceedings the presumption of innocence requires that certain conditions are met mainly in respect of the burden of proof, of legal presumptions of fact and law, of public statements by the trial court or other public officials regarding a defendant\u2019s guilt or innocence before the conclusion of the trial, of the privilege against self-incrimination and of pre-trial publicity. At the same time, the presumption of innocence as an aspect of the personality of the individual safeguards the honour and dignity of the individual. The presumption of innocence will be violated by comments or expressions of judicial opinion suggestive of guilt after an individual\u2019s acquittal of a criminal charge or following the discontinuance of criminal proceedings. The protection of the presumption of innocence has recently been reinforced with additional guarantees following the enactment of Directive EU\/2016\/343 \u201con the strengthening of certain aspects of the presumption of innocence and of the right to be present at the trial in criminal proceedings\u201d. The aim of this article is to analyze and\/or discuss the application of the presumption of innocence in the Cypriot legal order in light of the European Convention on Human Rights and the European Directive (EU) 2016\/343.<\/p>\n","protected":false},"author":1,"featured_media":2439,"comment_status":"open","ping_status":"open","sticky":false,"template":"","format":"standard","meta":{"site-sidebar-layout":"default","site-content-layout":"","ast-site-content-layout":"","site-content-style":"default","site-sidebar-style":"default","ast-global-header-display":"","ast-banner-title-visibility":"","ast-main-header-display":"","ast-hfb-above-header-display":"","ast-hfb-below-header-display":"","ast-hfb-mobile-header-display":"","site-post-title":"","ast-breadcrumbs-content":"","ast-featured-img":"","footer-sml-layout":"","theme-transparent-header-meta":"","adv-header-id-meta":"","stick-header-meta":"","header-above-stick-meta":"","header-main-stick-meta":"","header-below-stick-meta":"","astra-migrate-meta-layouts":"","footnotes":""},"categories":[6,8],"tags":[],"_links":{"self":[{"href":"https:\/\/cparaskeva.com\/wp-json\/wp\/v2\/posts\/2721"}],"collection":[{"href":"https:\/\/cparaskeva.com\/wp-json\/wp\/v2\/posts"}],"about":[{"href":"https:\/\/cparaskeva.com\/wp-json\/wp\/v2\/types\/post"}],"author":[{"embeddable":true,"href":"https:\/\/cparaskeva.com\/wp-json\/wp\/v2\/users\/1"}],"replies":[{"embeddable":true,"href":"https:\/\/cparaskeva.com\/wp-json\/wp\/v2\/comments?post=2721"}],"version-history":[{"count":0,"href":"https:\/\/cparaskeva.com\/wp-json\/wp\/v2\/posts\/2721\/revisions"}],"wp:featuredmedia":[{"embeddable":true,"href":"https:\/\/cparaskeva.com\/wp-json\/wp\/v2\/media\/2439"}],"wp:attachment":[{"href":"https:\/\/cparaskeva.com\/wp-json\/wp\/v2\/media?parent=2721"}],"wp:term":[{"taxonomy":"category","embeddable":true,"href":"https:\/\/cparaskeva.com\/wp-json\/wp\/v2\/categories?post=2721"},{"taxonomy":"post_tag","embeddable":true,"href":"https:\/\/cparaskeva.com\/wp-json\/wp\/v2\/tags?post=2721"}],"curies"